<table border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 width="95%"><TR><td bgcolor="#F7F7F7"><TABLE BORDER=0 cellpadding=4 border=0 cellspacing=1 WIDTH="100%"><TR bgcolor="#DEDFDF"><TD COLSPAN=2><CENTER><FONT SIZE="2" COLOR="#9f3215" FACE="Verdana">T O P I C  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R E V I E W</font></CENTER></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#ffffff"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">khelor</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Have been trying to interact with NPC's for awhile now.  Especially between fun time in BB.<P>I came to the conclussion that NPC interaction is very limited.  Even down to saying hail to some characters they don't respond.  <P>Understandably there are a number of characters in the game with some background etc, most of the gaurds in Qeynos have a small personality, but other characters don't have any or are limited.<P>Would it be difficult to attach some personality to characters?  A gamesmaster in an AD&D type scenario would try and give NPC's a bit of background, even if it was a gruff exterior.<P>In my roleplaying days (Way back), I would enjoy the atmosphere that a good GM could produce when entering and sitting around in a Tavern Inn.<P>You can enter a bar/tavern in qeynos, where NPC's stand around.  These are great spawning grounds for stories, and quests.  Making things more hustle and bustle at the inns, would entice people in.<P>If there is anyone on the Povar server in Qeynos, who fancies a sing song and drinking contest, give me a /tell some time  <IMG SRC="http://www.everlore.com/boards/EL/smile.gif"><P>Khelor of Qeynos<BR>Bards of Povar Guild</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#ffffff"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Ralas</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">I very much agree.. Other than in Qeynos you rarely get a reply and it is quite disturbing to go around 'Hail'ing everyone you see and not get a response at all.  I wish GM's could take a larger role into EverQuest and give people more quests, more things to talk about, and just to feel the presence (that spelled right?) of a GM. A GM in EQ should be like a GM in AD&D.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#ffffff"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Bazele</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">I am a GM in AD&D and I agree totally with what you say. All or most of the npc's in everquest should have some sort of personality or they are a waste of space. I also agree that the everquest Gm's should take more part in creating quests to make the game more interesting.</FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#ffffff"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">mordeas</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">i agree that every npc should say something to you when you hail them. right now it seems as though they only talk back to you if they have a quest. also i think that if more gm's and guides took part in everquest it would bring the game back from the hack and slash, camp a place for 20 hours game its turning into<P>your friendly mage mordeas<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#ffffff"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">Zhaak</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">I realize this is kind of off topic but I had to respond to what mordeas said.  I agree that NPCs with more personality could make the game a little more interesting but realistically they don't need it.  If you take some time to role play with other players you are going to get better interaction then you ever could out of a computer.  It can be much more rewarding too.  I can't count the number of times that I've been given help or an item from someone that I took the time to get to know.  <P>------------------<BR>Bashinly Yours,<P>Zhaak<BR>Bertoxxolus<BR></FONT></TD></TR><TR bgcolor="#ffffff"><TD valign=top><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">?????</FONT></TD><TD><FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana">I totall agree NPC's should be interactive characters not objects</FONT></TD></TR></TABLE></td></tr></table> 
</FONT>
